\begin_layout Standard
The power of Prela is best illustrated with an example.
 Consider query 16b from the Join Order Benchmark
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DBLP:journals/pvldb/LeisGMBK015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 whose SQL formulation spans 23 clauses,
 11 of which are used to specify join conditions.
 Figure
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:JOB-query-16b"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

 shows the complete Prela source for the same query.
 We will revisit this query in detail later,
 but the intent is already clear at a glance:
 it looks for movies made by American companies with keyword matching 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

character-name-in-title
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 then outputs the movie title along with the alias for each cast member.
 There are several notable differences between the Prela query and the SQL version.
 First,
 there is no explicit 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
FROM
\end_layout

\end_inset

 clause in Prela;
 instead,
 relations appear as arguments to 
\emph on
relation combinators
\emph default
 like 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.with
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.and
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.select
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 revealing the 
\emph on
structure
\emph default
 of the query.
 Similarly,
 join conditions are not specified by explicit join clauses,
 but by query structure.
 Finally,
 thanks to the algebraic nature of Prela,
 queries can be written in a compositional way:
 in the example,
 every subexpression,
 including 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
company.s(country).eq(
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

[us]
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
keyword.eq(...)
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
cast.s(person).s(alias).s(text)
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 is on its own a valid query,
 and they appear directly as inputs to relation combinators to build up the larger query.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reader may be surprised to learn that the query in Figure
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:JOB-query-16b"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

 is in fact regular Rust code.
 Indeed,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
company
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
country
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 etc.,
 are Rust variables,
 and combinators like 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.with
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.and
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.select
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 etc.,
 are Rust functions.
 In other words,
 Prela is an 
\emph on
embedded query language
\emph default
,
 or more simply,
 a 
\emph on
library
\emph default
.
 This means Prela queries seamlessly integrate with application code,
 and the programmer can pass in regular Rust functions as UDFs.
 Under the hood,
 every Prela query is also a query plan,
 since each relational combinator corresponds precisely to an operator in 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
.
 A common complaint in SQL is the difficulty of guiding the query optimizer when it fails to find an efficient plan;
 by contrast,
 the Prela user has complete control over all aspect of query planning,
 including join ordering,
 operator pushdown,
 materialization,
 and selection of physical data structures.
 This level of control is increasingly relevant in the age of AI,
 as it puts the user—
human or machine—
back in the driver seat of performance engineering.
 Nevertheless,
 this great power need not come with great responsibility,
 and Prela/
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
 can just as well serve as the 
\emph on
intermediate representation
\emph default
 underlying a query optimizer—
the implementation of which we leave as future work.
 Finally,
 Prela queries are surprisingly 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

closer to the metal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 than even the standard relational algebra,
 thanks again to the foundation of 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
.
 In our running example,
 variables like 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
country
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
keyword
\end_layout

\end_inset

 are backed directly by vectors in a column store,
 and relation combinators compile to efficient operations over the columns.
 
\end_layout

