\begin_layout Subsection
Data Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fundamental datatype of Prela is the 
\emph on
binary
\emph default
 relation.
 Although restricting relations to be binary may appear limiting,
 it is simple to recover the flexibility of multi-column tables with ones over only two columns:
 every relation with 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 columns is represented with 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 binary relations,
 each mapping the row number to the corresponding column entry.
 Figure
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Decomposition-of-a"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

 shows an example:
 a 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie
\end_layout

\end_inset

 relation with columns 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
title
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
year
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
keyword
\end_layout

\end_inset

 decomposes to 4 binary relations:
 the first maps each ID to its row,
 and the other 3 map each row to its title,
 year,
 and keyword,
 respectively.
 The special treatment of the ID column will make sense when we join across tables.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Decomposing a wide table into many binary tables may appear expensive:
 while the original table had 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 columns,
 the decomposed tables now span a total of 
\begin_inset Formula $2k$
\end_inset

 columns.
 However,
 since one column of each binary relation simply contains the row number,
 that column need not be explicitly stored,
 and each binary relation can be represented by a vector!
 In Section
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Implementation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

 we will also show how Prela's implementation eliminates the additional joins needed to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

re-assemble
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 a wide table from its columns.
 In other words,
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

binarization
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 takes a detour to arrive at the same physical representation found in column stores.
 This detour is nevertheless necessary,
 as it allows us to query the columns in a compositional way.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Prela queries are composed of operators applied to relational arguments,
 much like the classic Relational Algebra 
\emph on
à la 
\emph default
Codd.
 To reduce clutter,
 we will introduce the operators directly in Prela's surface syntax and omit their mathematical symbols.
 
\end_layout

