\begin_layout Plain Layout
company
\end_layout

\end_inset

 column from the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie
\end_layout

\end_inset

 table;
 right:
 decomposed columns from the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie_company
\end_layout

\end_inset

 table
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Left:-decomposed-"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Composition also plays the role of joins in Prela.
 Consider a 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie_company
\end_layout

\end_inset

 table with three columns:
 the company ID,
 name,
 and country,
 each of which becomes a binary relation in Prela as shown on the right of Figure
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Left:-decomposed-"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

.
 We also add a 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
company
\end_layout

\end_inset

 column to the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie
\end_layout

\end_inset

 table linking each movie to the ID of its production company.
 Now,
 we can look up the country of a movie's production company with 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie.s(company).s(id2row).s(country)
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.s()
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is shorthand for 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.select()
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
id2row
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the relation mapping company IDs to row numbers.
 Because joining via foreign keys almost always require 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

resolving
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the key to its row,
 Prela automatically inserts 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.s(id2row)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to key/foreign key joins,
 similar to how programming languages like Rust automatically dereference pointers upon a field access.
 This allows us to simply write 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie.s(company).s(country)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 which is pronounced 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

movie's company's country
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 This is also what happened on the last line of Figure
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:JOB-query-16b"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given that composition 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

throws away
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the join attributes,
 the reader may be wondering if there are certain SQL queries that Prela cannot express.
 Our answer is two-fold.
 On one hand,
 real world queries almost always join on key/foreign keys,
 and keys rarely serve any other purpose —
 it does not make sense to aggregate over them.
 So dropping the keys after the join is not a real sacrifice.
 On the other hand,
 it is true that 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
 is strictly less expressive than Codd's relational algebra.
 One approach to bridging this gap is to introduce the so-called 
\emph on
pairing operators
\emph default
 to 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default

\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DBLP:books/mk/freytagMV91/GyssensSG91"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In Prela,
 we propose an equivalent extension —
 the
\emph on
 
\emph default
\noun on
product
\noun default
 operator 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.and()
\end_layout

\end_inset

 —
 that is more practical for writing queries.
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
r.and(s)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 joins the relations on their first column,
 i.e.,
 
\begin_inset Formula $r\bowtie_{r.1=s.1}s$
\end_inset

.
 Crucially,
 the output is still a 
\emph on
binary
\emph default
 relation,
 whose first column is the intersection of 
\begin_inset Formula $r.1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s.1$
\end_inset

,
 and the second column is the Cartesian product of 
\begin_inset Formula $r.2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s.2$
\end_inset

 for each matching 
\begin_inset Formula $r.1=s.1$
\end_inset

.
 For example,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
title.and(year)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the relation mapping 0 to (The Godfather,
 1972),
 1 to (Seven Samurai,
 1954),
 and 2 to (Casablanca,
 1942).
 Combining with 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.select()
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 the expression 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie.select(title.and(year).and(keyword))
\end_layout

\end_inset

 implements the SQL query 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
SELECT * FROM movie
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next Prela operator exercised by Figure
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:JOB-query-16b"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

 is the 
\noun on
predicate
\noun default
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
r.eq(v)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 which returns all rows of 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
r
\end_layout

\end_inset

 whose right column equals 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
v
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Other predicates like 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.gt()
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (greater than),
 and 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.rx()
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (regular expression match) work the same way.
 There is also a generic 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
r.filt(p)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 operator that filters 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
r
\end_layout

\end_inset

 by any Boolean function 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
p
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Going back to the example,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
keyword.eq("character-name-in-title")
\end_layout

\end_inset

 returns rows in 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
keyword
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (which maps a movie to its keywords) such that the keyword is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

character-name-in-title
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

;
 the expression 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
company.s(country).eq("[us]")
\end_layout

\end_inset

 first composes 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
company
