\begin_layout Subsection
Grouping and Aggregation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just like the original form of Codd's relational algebra,
 the mathematical definition of 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
 does not support aggregation.
 It is however straightforward to add such operators:
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
r.reduce(g)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 groups 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
r
\end_layout

\end_inset

 by its first column,
 and applies 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
g
\end_layout

\end_inset

 per group to aggregate over the second column.
 It is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{r.1,g(r.2)}(r)$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
reduce
\end_layout

\end_inset

 alone is not very useful —
 for example,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
year.reduce(min)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 groups over the row number (a no-op) and returns the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
year
\end_layout

\end_inset

 relation as-is.
 To support nontrivial grouping,
 we need to introduce one last operation from the original 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
:
 the 
\noun on
inverse
\noun default
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
s.inv()
\end_layout

\end_inset

 simply flips the two columns of 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
s
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 We can now implement Prela's 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
r.group_by(s)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
s.inv().with(r.inv())
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{s.2,s.1}(s\ltimes_{s.1=r.2}r)$
\end_inset

 in relational algebra.
 For example,
 the first line of the Prela query in Figure
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Grouping-and-aggregation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

 desugars to 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
keyword.inv().with(movie.inv())
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 First,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
keyword.inv()
\end_layout

\end_inset

 flips the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
keyword
\end_layout

\end_inset

 relation to map each keyword to the rows it appears in;
 restricting with 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie.inv()
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is a no-op,
 but would be meaningful if 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie
\end_layout

\end_inset

 were already restricted by other predicates.
 Line 2 composes the result from line 1 with 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
year
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to obtain a mapping from keyword to year.
 Line 3 aggregates with 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
min
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to find the earliest year associated with each keyword.
 Note that in this process,
 each of 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.group_by()
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.select()
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.reduce()
\end_layout

\end_inset

 produces a valid binary relation,
 whereas in SQL,
 a 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
GROUP BY
\end_layout

\end_inset

 clause must be accompanied by aggregation in the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
SELECT
\end_layout

\end_inset

 clause.
 Finally,
 the last line of the Prela query in Figure
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Grouping-and-aggregation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

 implements the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
HAVING
\end_layout

\end_inset

 clause in the SQL query,
 simply by filtering with the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.gt()
\end_layout

\end_inset

 predicate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Grouping by multiple columns can be achieved with the help of 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.and()
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 for example 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie.group_by(keyword.and(year))
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 To aggregate over multiple columns,
 we can pass in a function that reduces a group of tuples at once.
 Prela also provides another form 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
r.fold(o)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
o
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is a binary 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

combine
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 function.
 This allows more ergonomic multi-column aggregates like:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
r.fold(|(x,y),
 (dx,dy)| (x+dx,
 min(y,dy)))
\end_layout

\end_inset

Aggregation without grouping is supported with the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.reduce_all()
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.fold_all()
\end_layout

\end_inset

 operators.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
What about aggregation without grouping?
 We can group by the 
\emph on
abstract relation
\emph default
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
unit
\end_layout

\end_inset

 which is a constant function returning 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
()
\end_layout

\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie.group_by(unit)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 returns a relation mapping 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
()
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to all rows in the movie table,
 then 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie.group_by(unit).select(year).reduce(min)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 finds the earliest year for all movies.
 However,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
unit.inv()
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is an infinite relation!
 For this reason,
 Prela provides a 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.reduce_all()
\end_layout

\end_inset

 operator that simply aggregates without grouping.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Looking back at the example in Figure
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:JOB-query-16b"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

,
 we see another,
 more intuitive way to understand the query:
 pretend that there are 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie
\end_layout

\end_inset

 objects with field 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
company
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
keyword
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
title
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
cast
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
company
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is its own object with field 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
country
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 and similarly for 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
cast
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
person
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
alias
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Then the Prela query appears to access fields and apply predicates to them.
 This is not accidental.
 Central to the design of both 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
 and Prela is the focus on binary relations,
 which closely models both attributes and relationships 
\emph on
à la
\emph default
 Entity/Relationship.
 Modern business logic usually start life as an E/R diagram,
 and the application code —
 commonly written in some object-oriented language —
 naturally mirrors the E/R model.
 Built with a set of compositional operators,
 Prela queries blend into the surrounding application,
 obviating the need for ORMs.
 The binary relation foundation also paves the way to support emerging workloads over nested documents and graph data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Implementation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Implementation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A Prela query defines a 
\emph on
query tree
\emph default
 whose inner nodes are query combinators and whose leaves are data.
 For example,
 the query 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie.with(year.eq(1997)).s(title.and(keyword))
\end_layout

\end_inset

defines the following tree:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
begin{figure}[h]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
begin{forest}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
for tree={s sep=10mm,
 l sep=1mm}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[select
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
  [with
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
    [movie]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
    [eq
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
      [year]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
      [1997]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
    ]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
  ]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
  [and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
    [title]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
    [keyword]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
  ]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
end{forest}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
caption{Query tree for 
\backslash
texttt{select(with(movie,eq(year,
 1997)),
 and(title,
 keyword))}}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
end{figure}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

 A query tree is isomorphic to the query's AST.
 Moreover,
 Prela lacks a query optimizer:
 the query tree 
\emph on
is
\emph default
 the query plan.
 Thus,
 Prela's surface syntax is transparent to the underlying execution plan.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A naive implementation of this plan would propagate data from leaves to root,
 materializing 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A = year.eq(1997)
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
B = movie.with(A)
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
C = title.and(keyword)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 before finally iterating over 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
B.s(C)
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This approach must store the entire relation 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
B
\end_layout

\end_inset

 while computing 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
C
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 and traverses the data multiple times to compute each intermediate relation.
 A pull-based query engine 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DBLP:journals/tkde/Graefe94"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 avoids materializing intermediate relations all at once and pipelines the data passes,
 but still materializes each intermediate tuple;
 likewise for vectorized engines 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DBLP:conf/cidr/BonczZN05"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 By contrast,
 an ideal column store implementation would compile the query to a single pass with no dynamic dispatch 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DBLP:journals/pvldb/Neumann11"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 as in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:compiled_query"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
for i in 0..len(movie)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
    if year[i] == 1997
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
        print(movie[i],
 title[i],
 keyword[i])
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:compiled_query"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie.with(year.eq(1997)).s(title.and(keyword))
\end_layout

\end_inset

 compiled to a fused loop.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking inspiration from functional compilers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DBLP:conf/fpca/GillLJ93"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 Prela implements query combinators in Continuation-Passing Style,
 thereby recovering fused-loop execution.
 The basic idea is that combinators push computation down from the query root to its leaves instead of pulling data up from leaves to root.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More specifically,
 we can think of the nodes in a query tree as higher-order functions accepting continuations.
 For example,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie.s(title)(print)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 prints each 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
(id,
 title)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 pair in 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie.s(title)
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In the interest of compactness,
 we'll write 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
select(lhs,
 rhs)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to represent the higher-order function (i.e.
 the node) and 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
select(lhs,
 rhs,
 k)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for its application to 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
k
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
lhs
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
rhs
\end_layout

\end_inset

 are themselves nodes in the query tree and hence can also accept continuations.
 In addition,
 we must wrap source nodes in one of two 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

accessors
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
drive
\end_layout

\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
probe
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
drive(rel,
 k)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 applies 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
k
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to each row of 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
rel
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 while 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
probe(rel,
 i,
 k)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 first looks 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
i
\end_layout

\end_inset

 up in 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
rel
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and applies 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
k
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to the result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us illustrate the implementation of CPS combinators with the following simple query 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
select(drive(movie),
 and(probe(title),
 probe(keyword)))
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Here are the definitions of the combinators:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
select(lhs,
 rhs,
 k) = lhs(|x,
 y| rhs(y,
 |z| k(x,
 z)))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
and(lhs,
 rhs,
 i,
 k) = lhs(x,
 |y| rhs(x,
 |x| k(x,
 (y,
 z))))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
drive(rel,
 k) = for i in 0..len(rel) { k(i,
 i) }
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
probe(rel,
 i,
 k) = k(rel[i])
